Many composers of the past have been allergic to the term \emph{music theory}. We find evidence of this when Schoenberg says, ''...the usual music theorist has no practical skills at all -- he is no master'' \parencite[p. 7]{schoenberg2010theory}. The term \gls{musical-practitioner} is used regularly in this book to distinguish between those who \emph{think} about music, and those who have demonstrated \emph{great skill} in bringing it about. Oftentimes when great musical practitioners speak, their words aren't directly recorded, and this leads to the creation of an \gls{oral tradition}, which is distorted, diluted, and proliferated over time. This book is an \emph{attempt} to explain, reinforce, and clarify the oral tradition surrounding \BarryFull and his work.

For the purposes of this \emph{practically-oriented} text, we will define \gls{musical-theory} narrowly as any system that attempts to describe how music is experienced by the listener. This sits in strong contrast to our definition of \gls{musical-practice}, which is essentially anything a great musical practitioner says or does. We are giving this leeway to great practitioners of the past because they have, at the very least, demonstrated great musical ability. This ability though, doesn't guarantee that they will be able to adequately explain how they work their magic. But if we are careful, we can obtain great insights from them in regards to how music \emph{really} works.
